Denkraum

A Docker-ready Retrieval-Augmented Generation API built with .NET 8, Clean Architecture, PostgreSQL, pgvector, ClosedXML, and Ollama.

Denkraum is a backend RAG platform for indexing local Excel workbooks, converting worksheet rows into readable semantic chunks, generating embeddings, storing vectors in PostgreSQL with pgvector, searching spreadsheet knowledge semantically, and returning grounded chat answers with source citations. The system is split into `Denkraum.Api`, `Denkraum.Application`, `Denkraum.Domain`, and `Denkraum.Infrastructure`, keeping controllers thin while validation, result handling, document workflows, semantic search, grounded chat orchestration, dashboard summaries, and service contracts live in the Application layer. Infrastructure contains EF Core persistence, pgvector configuration, ClosedXML workbook reading, Ollama embedding and chat clients, startup indexing, file watching, and PostgreSQL-backed vector search.

The project is designed as a polished portfolio/CV backend project that can be run locally with `docker compose up --build`, starting PostgreSQL on port `5432` and the API on `http://localhost:8080`. It indexes `.xlsx` files from the local `data/` directory, applies EF Core migrations on startup, exposes Scalar API documentation at `/docs`, logs structured events with Serilog, validates request DTOs with FluentValidation, returns RFC7807 ProblemDetails for failures, and supports document indexing, document listing, document deletion, semantic search, chat sessions, grounded question answering, and dashboard counts. Configuration is environment-based for Docker and includes PostgreSQL connection strings, Ollama base URL, API key, chat model, embedding model, data directory, and embedding batch size.

Verification commands are `dotnet restore` and `dotnet build`; the solution builds with nullable reference types enabled, warnings treated as errors, and zero compiler warnings. Runtime verification requires PostgreSQL with pgvector plus valid Ollama API credentials. Intentionally excluded for this version are authentication, frontend UI, distributed queues, Redis, multi-tenant authorization, and hand-rolled LLM orchestration frameworks.
